# "Changes while in the air": the slope is recomputed each tick as (end-output)/
# remaining_time, so changing `end` mid-flight makes the output continue SMOOTHLY
# from its current level to the new end, still arriving exactly when phase hits 1.
# start=0, end=0.5, duration=1 s (tickrate 10). At t5 end jumps to 1.0: output is
# at 0.2, remaining 0.6 s -> new slope 1.333/s, so it accelerates and reaches 1.0
# at t10 (no sudden step). phase is the INTERNAL CLOCK ("measures which part of
# the transient has been run through already"), NOT the normalized output
# position: it keeps running 0->1 linearly with time, unaffected by the end
# change (here: 0.5 at t5, the halfway point of the 1 s duration).
tickrate 10
patch <<<
[transient]
    start    = 0
    end      = I1
    duration = 1
    output   = O1
    phase    = O2
>>>
@0 set I1 0.5
@4 expect O1 0.2 tol 1e-4
# end -> 1.0 at t5: smooth continuation (no jump), faster slope
@5 set I1 1.0
@5 expect O1 0.33333 tol 1e-4
# internal clock: halfway through the 1 s duration, regardless of the end change
# (the normalized output position would be 0.333 here -- that is NOT phase)
@5 expect O2 0.5 tol 1e-4
@6 expect O1 0.46667 tol 1e-4
@7 expect O2 0.7 tol 1e-4
@7 expect O1 0.6 tol 1e-4
@10 expect O1 1.0 tol 1e-4
@10 expect O2 1.0 tol 1e-4
